### Formula 1

From the unit circle sin^2x +cos^2 x=1
That's pretty intuitive.

### Formula 2

divide both sides by cos^2x to get,
sin^2x/cos^2x= 1/cos^2x
sin/cos=tan and so sin^2x/cos ^2x= tan ^2x.
1/cos^2x=sec^2x
so, tan^2x +1= sec^2x.

### Formula 3

divide both sides by sin^2x to get,
cos^2x/sin^2x= 1/sin^2x
cos/sin=cot and so cos^2x/sin ^2x= cot ^2x.
1/sin^2x=cosec^2x
so, cot^2x +1= cosec^2x.

# Formula 4 and 5
These two come from the definition of even and odd functions.
Cos is even, it's a rule of this great universe.
Sin is odd its a rule of this great universe.
a function is even if F(x)= F(-x).
A function is odd if F(x)=- F (x)
cos x=cos(-x)
sin x= -sin x

 #Formula 6 AND 7

sin x= sin x+2pi
cos x= cos x +2pi
since by adding 2 pi, we are doing circumference navigation around the circle and we will get the same result.

#Formula 8
sine is sumthing that switches- mnemonic
sin(x+y)= sinxcosy+cosxsiny

cosine is kinda opposite of this
cos (x+y)= cosxcosy-sinxsiny

# Double Angle Formulas
Sin(x+x)= sinxcosx+cosxsinx
Sin2x=2sinxcosx

Cos(x+x)=cosxsinx+sinxsinx
Cos2x= cos^2x+sin^2x
tan(x+y)= tanx + tany/ 1- tanxtany
tan(x+x)= 2tanx/1- tan^2x
Sin^2x= 1/2[1-cos2x]
Cos ^2x= 1/2[1+cos2x]
For tan you can derive from the above

2sinAcosB=sin(A+B)+sin(A-B)
2cosAcosB= cos (A+B) + cos (A-B)
-2sinAsinB= cos (A+B) - cos (A-B)

the integral of : dx/x^2+a^2= 1/a tan^-1 x/a +c



